  { q: 'What is the difference between lossy and lossless compression?', a: 'Lossy compression (JPEG, WebP) permanently discards some image data to achieve smaller sizes. Lossless compression (PNG, WebP lossless) reduces file size without any data loss — but the reduction is smaller.' },
  { q: 'Should I use JPEG or WebP for web images?', a: 'WebP is the modern standard: it achieves 25–35% smaller files than JPEG at the same quality. However, very old browsers do not support WebP. For maximum compatibility, use JPEG; for modern web projects, use WebP.' },
  { q: 'Can I compress a PNG file?', a: 'PNG uses lossless compression, so the browser tool repackages it without quality loss. For significant reduction, convert the PNG to JPEG or WebP (if it has no transparency).' },
