<h2>Why Image Compression Matters</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Page speed:</strong> Images are typically the largest assets on a web page. Google's Core Web Vitals directly measure how quickly images load. Compressing images is the single fastest win for page performance.</li>
  <li><strong>Storage:</strong> A folder of 200 uncompressed photos from a DSLR can be 2–4 GB. The same photos at 80% JPEG quality take under 300 MB.</li>
  <li><strong>Email:</strong> Gmail and Outlook have 25 MB attachment limits. A batch of product photos often exceeds this without compression.</li>
  <li><strong>Upload limits:</strong> CMS platforms, social networks, and form builders often limit uploads to 2–5 MB per image.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Compress an Image Free Online</h2>

