<h2>Choosing the Right Quality Setting</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Quality 90–100%:</strong> Near-lossless. Good for archival or print. File size reduction is small (10–20%).</li>
  <li><strong>Quality 75–85%:</strong> Best balance. Visually identical to the original at normal viewing size. 40–60% smaller.</li>
  <li><strong>Quality 50–70%:</strong> Significant reduction (60–80%). Minor artefacts visible in high-detail regions on close inspection.</li>
  <li><strong>Below 50%:</strong> Severe quality loss. Only suitable for thumbnails or previews.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Compress Images on Desktop</h2>

<p><strong>Windows:</strong> Paint doesn't offer quality control. Use the browser tool above, or install IrfanView (free) for batch compression.</p>
<p><strong>Mac:</strong> Preview → Export → reduce quality slider. Or use the browser tool for no-install simplicity.</p>

<h2>Compress Images for WhatsApp / Telegram</h2>

<p>
  Messaging apps automatically compress images on send, but you lose control over the output. If you need to send a specific quality level, compress first using the Image Compressor, then send the compressed file to avoid double compression.
</p>

